subject: Add readability-redundant-* checks
commitMessage:
Add readability-redundant-* checks

There's a number of redundancies in our code that clang can sanitize
out.  Fix the existing problems, and enable the checks.

Signed-off-by: Ed Tanous <edtanous@google.com>
Change-Id: Ie63d7b7f0777b702fbf1b23a24e1bed7b4f5183b

I am struggling a bit here.. 
We are initializing other types (bools, int, etc)
The bools and int are coming from readability-redundant-member-init, I'm pretty sure.
I actually don't prefer a few of these changes but this will lead to more consistent code and I don't have a huge preference

I am struggling just a bit here. 
To me the code on the left is slightly more readable.

I guess it's subjective.  I find the new one more readable, just because you don't have to worry about the distinction between
parseIpsProperties(..) == true
parseIpsProperties(..) != false
parseIpsProperties(..) == false
parseIpsProperties(..) != true

when you're reading, there's only 2 option to logic through instead of 4.  Quite possible my brain works differently than others though, and this is highly subjective.

IMO, I think being consistent is the most important thing, which, from your other comment it sounds like you agree.

> I think being consistent is the most important thing

+1.
